  "prompt": "How does international law intersect with national laws on money laundering?",
  "response": "International law intersects with national laws on money laundering through several key mechanisms:\n\n1. Global Regulatory Frameworks\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Basel Committee guidelines\n- International standards for combating financial crimes\n\n2. Shared Legal Principles\n- Know Your Customer (KYC) requirements\n- Suspicious transaction reporting\n- Customer due diligence protocols\n- Cross-border information sharing mechanisms\n\n3. Enforcement Cooperation\n- Mutual legal assistance treaties\n- Extradition agreements\n- Joint investigative efforts\n- Coordinated financial intelligence unit collaborations\n\n4. Compliance Mechanisms\n- International banking regulations\n- Harmonized anti-money laundering (AML) standards\n- Uniform reporting requirements\n- Consistent risk assessment methodologies\n\n5. Jurisdictional Coordination\n- Addressing legal differences between countries\n- Establishing common definitions of financial crimes\n- Creating transnational prosecution frameworks\n- Developing standardized investigative procedures\n\nThese intersections aim to create comprehensive, interconnected approaches to preventing and detecting money laundering across different legal systems and national boundaries.",
